      <section id="measuring-visibility" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Prompt-Set Testing and Measurement: The Practitioner Protocol</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>LLM visibility is measurable through systematic prompt testing — and prompt-set testing is the primary feedback loop that tells you whether your implementation is working.</strong>
          Without a testing programme, you cannot distinguish tactics that drive citation improvements from those that have no effect. This section covers how to build and run a prompt-set testing programme from scratch.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 1: Build Your Query Set</h3>
        <p>
          Select 20–50 queries that represent your brand's core informational and commercial intent space. Include: category-level queries ("best GEO agencies UK"), problem-awareness queries ("how to get my brand cited by ChatGPT"), comparison queries ("GEO vs SEO"), and branded queries ("GEOoptimised review"). Organise queries by intent type and priority. Your query set is both your measurement instrument and your content roadmap — every query you cannot find your brand in is a content or signal gap to close.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 2: Establish a Baseline</h3>
        <p>
          Before making any changes, run all queries across ChatGPT (with Browse enabled), Perplexity, Gemini, Copilot, and Google AI Overviews. For each query, record: whether your brand is mentioned (yes/no), whether it is cited with a source link, its position if mentioned alongside competitors, and whether the description is accurate. This baseline is your starting point for measuring all future attribution.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 3: Record and Score</h3>
        <p>
          The primary metric is <em>citation rate</em>: the percentage of target queries for which your brand is mentioned in the AI response. Track this per platform and in aggregate. Secondary metrics: citation accuracy (percentage of mentions with a correct, non-outdated description), citation position (average rank in multi-source responses), and citation depth (percentage of mentions that include a source link rather than an unlinked mention).
        </p>

        <h3>Step 4: Attribute Changes</h3>
        <p>
          When you deploy a change — a content rewrite, a schema addition, a new Wikidata attribute — note the date and which pages or signals were affected. Re-test your query set two to four weeks later and compare results. Changes that move citation rate on specific query types can be directly attributed to the corresponding tactic. This attribution data is what justifies continued investment and informs prioritisation of the next sprint.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 5: Scale with Tooling</h3>
        <p>
          Manual testing is feasible for query sets under 50 queries on two or three platforms. Above that scale, dedicated AI visibility platforms automate prompt testing and provide trend data over time. Platforms including Profound, Semrush AI Toolkit, and Brandwatch AI cover all major platforms and export structured citation data. For a full comparison of available tools and pricing, see our <a href="/geo-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO tools directory</a>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The KPI framework for presenting measurement results to senior stakeholders — citation frequency, AI share of voice, brand accuracy score, and cross-platform reach — is covered in the <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a> strategy guide. For cross-platform measurement considerations specific to individual model behaviours, see our guide to <a href="/cross-model-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">cross-model optimisation</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

